{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01XFgVbMjE6VaxARBnsr7uua","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_013cFv28r6CURRNLKajQf2PY","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"kubectl -n spark-pi create configmap config-audit --from-literal=findings.txt=\"$(cat <<'FINDINGS'\nSPARK-PI NAMESPACE COMPLIANCE AUDIT\n====================================\nAudit Date : 2026-06-25\nNamespace  : spark-pi\nAuditor    : Automated read-only inspection\n\nSCOPE\n-----\nRBAC roles and bindings, service accounts, resource limits, image provenance,\njob and deployment security contexts, network policies, and overall namespace\nposture.  No changes were made to the cluster during this audit.\n\nCUSTOMISATIONS DETECTED (non-default from rollback-rehearsal ConfigMap)\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n1. Image pinned: apache/spark:latest -> apache/spark:3.5.3 (all workloads)\n2. Resource limits added to spark-master, spark-worker, and spark-pi job\n3. ServiceAccount changed from 'default' to dedicated 'spark-pi' SA\n4. Custom Role 'spark-pi-role' and RoleBinding 'spark-pi-role-binding' added\n5. spark-worker replicas reduced from 2 to 1\n\n=== COMPLIANT / CORRECTLY CONFIGURED ===\n\n[PASS] RBAC-01: Dedicated ServiceAccount\n  Service account 'spark-pi' is used by all workloads (master, worker, job)\n  instead of the 'default' SA. Reduces blast radius if credentials are\n  compromised.\n\n[PASS] RBAC-02: Role exists and is namespace-scoped\n  Role 'spark-pi-role' is a namespaced Role (not ClusterRole), correctly\n  limiting privileges to the spark-pi namespace only.\n\n[PASS] RBAC-03: RoleBinding subject matches dedicated SA\n  'spark-pi-role-binding' binds only to SA 'spark-pi' in namespace 'spark-pi'.\n  No wildcard subjects or cluster-level subjects.\n\n[PASS] IMAGE-01: Specific image tag pinned (not 'latest')\n  All containers (spark-master, spark-worker, spark-submit) use\n  apache/spark:3.5.3 — a specific version tag rather than 'latest'.\n  Prevents uncontrolled upgrades on pod restart.\n\n[PASS] RESOURCE-01: CPU and memory requests set on all containers\n  spark-master : cpu=200m req / 500m limit; memory=512Mi req / 1Gi limit\n  spark-worker : cpu=200m req / 500m limit; memory=512Mi req / 1Gi limit\n  spark-pi job : cpu=200m req / 500m limit; memory=512Mi req / 1Gi limit\n  Prevents resource starvation of the node and enables scheduler placement.\n\n[PASS] RESOURCE-02: Memory and CPU limits set on all containers\n  Hard limits are configured, preventing runaway workloads from consuming\n  unbounded node resources.\n\n[PASS] JOB-01: Job restart policy is 'Never'\n  The spark-pi Job uses restartPolicy=Never and backoffLimit=0, preventing\n  repeated retries on failure and avoiding duplicate side effects.\n\n[PASS] JOB-02: Job completed successfully\n  Pod spark-pi-d9w86 shows Status=Completed, Job status=succeeded:1.\n\n=== GAPS / NON-COMPLIANT FINDINGS ===\n\n[FAIL] SEC-CTX-01 (HIGH): No pod-level security context on deployments or job\n  spark-master, spark-worker, and the spark-pi job all have securityContext: {}\n  at the pod spec level. Missing controls:\n    - runAsNonRoot: true  (containers may run as root, UID 0)\n    - runAsUser / runAsGroup  (no specific UID enforced)\n    - fsGroup  (no filesystem group ownership set)\n  Recommendation: Set runAsNonRoot: true and a non-zero runAsUser (e.g., 1000)\n  in the pod-level securityContext for all three workloads.\n\n[FAIL] SEC-CTX-02 (HIGH): No container-level security context on any container\n  All containers (spark-master, spark-worker, spark-submit) have no container-\n  level securityContext set. Missing controls:\n    - allowPrivilegeEscalation: false  (containers can gain elevated privileges)\n    - readOnlyRootFilesystem: true  (writable root filesystem)\n    - capabilities.drop: [\"ALL\"]  (all Linux capabilities retained)\n  Recommendation: Add a container securityContext with allowPrivilegeEscalation:\n  false, readOnlyRootFilesystem: true (with tmpDir volume mounts as needed),\n  and capabilities: drop: [ALL] to each container spec.\n\n[FAIL] NET-01 (HIGH): No NetworkPolicy defined\n  kubectl get networkpolicy -n spark-pi returns an empty list. All pods in\n  spark-pi can communicate freely with any other pod or service in the cluster\n  (unrestricted east-west traffic). There is also no egress restriction.\n  Recommendation: Define a default-deny NetworkPolicy and explicit allow rules\n  for: spark-master <-> spark-worker (port 7077), spark-submit -> spark-master\n  (port 7077), and necessary DNS egress (port 53 UDP).\n\n[FAIL] RBAC-04 (MEDIUM): Role 'spark-pi-role' is over-privileged\n  The role grants create/get/list/watch/delete/update/patch on pods, services,\n  configmaps, and persistentvolumeclaims. The 'delete', 'update', and 'patch'\n  verbs on configmaps and PVCs are broader than a SparkPi job typically requires.\n  In particular, the ability to delete pods and patch configmaps within the\n  namespace could be exploited if a workload is compromised.\n  Recommendation: Apply least-privilege — restrict to the minimum verbs actually\n  needed by the Spark driver (typically get/list/watch on pods/services; create\n  on pods for executor launch if using cluster mode).\n\n[FAIL] IMAGE-02 (MEDIUM): Image referenced by mutable tag, not digest\n  Image 'apache/spark:3.5.3' is referenced by a tag, which is mutable and can\n  be overwritten in the registry without the Kubernetes manifest changing. This\n  breaks supply-chain integrity guarantees.\n  imagePullPolicy is IfNotPresent, meaning if the tag is compromised and the\n  image is already cached on the node, the compromised version will NOT be pulled.\n  Recommendation: Reference images by immutable digest\n  (e.g., apache/spark@sha256:<digest>) and enforce via an admission controller\n  (e.g., OPA/Kyverno policy).\n\n[FAIL] PROBE-01 (LOW): No liveness or readiness probes on spark-master or spark-worker\n  Neither deployment defines livenessProbe or readinessProbe. A hung Spark\n  master will not be detected and restarted automatically, and a not-yet-ready\n  worker will receive traffic from the master's scheduler prematurely.\n  Recommendation: Add readinessProbe on the Spark UI port (8080/8081) or a\n  custom health endpoint, and a livenessProbe with an appropriate\n  initialDelaySeconds.\n\n=== SUMMARY ===\n\n  Correctly configured : 7 checks (PASS)\n  Gaps identified      : 6 checks (FAIL)\n    HIGH severity      : 3  (SEC-CTX-01, SEC-CTX-02, NET-01)\n    MEDIUM severity    : 2  (RBAC-04, IMAGE-02)\n    LOW severity       : 1  (PROBE-01)\n\nPriority remediation order:\n  1. Add pod and container securityContext to all workloads (SEC-CTX-01/02)\n  2. Define NetworkPolicy with default-deny + explicit allow rules (NET-01)\n  3. Tighten RBAC role to least-privilege verbs (RBAC-04)\n  4. Switch image references to SHA256 digest pinning (IMAGE-02)\n  5. Add liveness/readiness probes to deployments (PROBE-01)\n\nNOTE: The 'rollback-rehearsal' ConfigMap is an operational artifact documenting\nthe pre-change baseline. It contains no secrets and poses no direct risk, but\nshould be removed or access-controlled once the change window closes to avoid\nexposing internal rollback procedures.\nFINDINGS\n)\" 2>&1","description":"Create config-audit ConfigMap with compliance findings"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1586,"cache_read_input_tokens":35052,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1586},"output_tokens":34,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bf8e4292-3249-4061-8505-81eed68f4945","uuid":"713ea4f7-6a5e-449b-a3fd-5ffeac5ac5ce","request_id":"req_011CcQ7WkQ14Ueep1jN1HbAX"}
